from . import _utilities

__all__ = [
]
```

> The main reason is that if multiple radios are running on the same chip (e.g. bluetooth), we probably don't want the whole chip to be reset when the Thread host starts, resetting only the needed part by software is more graceful. This increases complexity though.

Thanks @jinran-google. It makes sense. Overall the code LGTM. I just added few smaller suggestions below.

But thinking more about this, I have an idea/suggestion for a rather different overall approach which I'd like to bring up.

- I understand the main goal/reason that we don't want to reset the entire chip if there are multiple radio (BLE, etc) on it when Thread starts.
- The solution in this PR is to add mechnasim to just reset the radio.
- But we are leaving all other platform modules that OT may use and the `otInstance` itself to continue to run as before (e.g. `Alarm/Timer` platform, or UART, etc.).  I guess this is fine and works for RCP (for now).

What we really want is that when we get a reset command (from host) to not reset the whole chip. We really want to have all the platform modules reset and then reinit the `otInstance` (clear all RAM variable) and start running `otInstance` fresh.

I think we can realize this differently:
- From `Instance::Reset()` we call `otPlatReset()` which we currently assume would reset the whole chip.
- We can change the implementation of `otPlatReset()` in platform layer to not trigger chip reset, but instead it can reset all the plaform modules (Radio, alaram, etc). 
- In OT code, we change the `Instance::Reset()` such that after calling `otPlatReset()` we call `Finalize()` immediately followed by `InitSingle()` call again (to reinit the `otInstance`). 
  - If the `otPlatReset()` does actually reset the chip, then we won't get to the `Finalize()` and `InitSingle()` callls (which is fine).
  - If the `otPlatReset()` resets all the platform components/modules, then we are reinitializing the `otInstance` to start fresh (which clears all RAM variables). 

I think this can work. The main advantages I see is that it resets all components without resetting the chip. It delegates the reseting of platform modules to the platform implementation itself which can reset all platform modules (radio, timer, any other platform module we may use in future)... It avoids the need for us to add mechanism in OT To handle reset of one platform components (like reseting radio only - which can be tricky to do).

Thoughts?



-----------

Edit: The more I think about it, the more I feel we should have platform layer code handle all of this, including the `Finalize()` an re-`Init()` of the `otInstance`.
- The platform layer contains the OS and knows how it wants to handle reset request from OT
- The platform layer creates and owns the `otInstance` itself (from its main/run-loop code), so it can re-init it when needed
- The platform layer need to ensure all OT tasklets and callback are called from same OS context (e.g. same RTOS task or same posix thread, etc), so it knows and can decide whether it wants to re-init the RTOS task or not.
- We provide an exmplae run-loop/main implementation and some related functions in `openthread-system.h` and `examples/app/{ncp/cli}/main.cpp` where we use `otSysPseudoResetWasRequested()` and then restart the loop. I think same mechansim/model can be used to implement platform reset on products without a full chip reset.
```c++
int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    otInstance *instance;

    [...]

pseudo_reset:

    otSysInit(argc, argv);

#if OPENTHREAD_CONFIG_MULTIPLE_INSTANCE_ENABLE
    // Call to query the buffer size
    (void)otInstanceInit(NULL, &otInstanceBufferLength);

    // Call to allocate the buffer
    otInstanceBuffer = (uint8_t *)malloc(otInstanceBufferLength);
    assert(otInstanceBuffer);

    // Initialize OpenThread with the buffer
    instance = otInstanceInit(otInstanceBuffer, &otInstanceBufferLength);
#else
    instance = otInstanceInitSingle();
#endif
    assert(instance);

    otAppNcpInit(instance);

    while (!otSysPseudoResetWasRequested())
    {
        otTaskletsProcess(instance);
        otSysProcessDrivers(instance);
    }

    otInstanceFinalize(instance);
#if OPENTHREAD_CONFIG_MULTIPLE_INSTANCE_ENABLE
    free(otInstanceBuffer);
#endif

    goto pseudo_reset;

    return 0;
}
```

A couple comments; 

1. Why are some of test assert values are changed?
2. Can you make sure we can copy the object ID spread to 2 lines by double clicking it? This is really important for UX.

@sophiazhi Thanks a lot for your work. LGTM.

I am approving this PR on the basis that the model achieves decent accuracy for its size and that unblocks Mutimodal. On the cons side, we are using ported weights from an unofficial repo which seem to be lagging by 5 accuracy points comparing to the paper. To mitigate this I have:
1. [Pinged](https://github.com/pytorch/vision/pull/6412#issuecomment-1219687434) the author of the repo to clarify the exact inference setup they use.
2. Started an internal job (id 55651) to train the network from scratch and potentially replace the weights if we get better accuracy.

Since the gap in accuracy is on the borderline of what we usually consider acceptable and because I've made multiple commits on the PR, I would like a second opinion on how we should progress here.

@jdsgomes @langong347 Please let me know your thoughts.
